Comment: “the other hand one finger” (one finger of the other hand)
(be is same as we it = and)
If the native begins with the little finger of the left hand he will call it monou, one
but he may add to it the next finger and call them morere, two or he may say they are “two.”
The third finger he naims kai; ane is the conjunction “and,” hence rere kaiane means little finger and the fourth are two fingers and kai added to them they become three fingers.

Morere-morere suggests that these natives are inclined to think in pairs or couples; they certainly do group the fingers into two pairs when they wish to illustrate what they mean by “four.” Taking it that they count thus, morere, one pair, morere-morere, another pair. The mo is in frequent use and means “ another,” “more.”
Kaupu, five, i.e., a collection or company, i.e., the fingers of the clenched hand.
‘showing another top part’, i.e. beginning another unit
‘and, plus’; lama ‘a pair’, i.e. a man + two more
‘side, half’; konda-pe ‘to add on’, i.e. a man + a half
i.e. a man and a half and another top part
i.e. a man and a pair at the top of a unit
i.e. a man and a pair at the top of a unit and another finger
‘two men and at the top part another finger’
‘a man and a man’ = ten times ten, i.e. 100

‘palm of hand’; Glossed by Lean (Vol. 9:28) as ‘here is the flat object, e.g. bridge’ but I believe this is incorrect. Bridge, which is the same word as ‘corpse’ (or sometimes ‘body’) in many Engan languages, is tó-ko (Lang 1973:131) in E and to-ko in S, which in PE is *tro-nko. However, in S, body is lo-ke.
‘top part of something’; Probably from wakyátae ‘exposed top part’ (Lang 1973:111).
‘a man and half that is a hand’
‘a man with five and jump one’

watangïn ‘last bunch (of bananas) to emerge’ + ila ‘morota frond’. The word watangïn seems to be used in a more general sense to refer to the last of a series (it also refers to the ‘pinky finger’, for example). Comment: the root is poedȯė = (unit of) ten; the prefix ma (with s short a) means = become.
Ěsa becomes sa when the preceding word ends in an a, e, or o.
Ěpat can become pat, see above. Read: mapoedȯė wo pat
Ěněm can become něm, for the same reason. Read: mapoedȯė wo něm
The root of maatoes is atoes = a hundred
There is no term for ten thousand

Comment: NB: In fact no one was mastering numbers when we first came, then the people encouraged themselves to use them and came up with this. This system is not the way people naturally counted before we came, they used TP numbers. If we want to be understood by the average Kwanga man we use TP numbers.

Kawi also uses cardinal numbers borrowed from Sanskrit.

Note that in Ampibabo-Lauje the coordinator ma is generally used only for the final single digit.
